00:44:30,689 --> 00:44:36,691
And then from there on start the darker blue bars at the start of the release of the gold pass.

705
00:44:36,691 --> 00:44:40,773
And as you can see, there's a lot more monthly unique payers.

706
00:44:40,773 --> 00:44:45,355
And what's even cooler is the gold pass actually impacted our economy in a way that

707
00:44:45,355 --> 00:44:48,476
we have more payers and everyone's paying less.

708
00:44:49,293 --> 00:44:52,654
We succeeded in broadening our player base,

709
00:44:52,654 --> 00:44:54,335
making the game more healthy,

710
00:44:54,335 --> 00:44:57,256
giving a price point that more people are comfortable paying.

711
00:44:57,256 --> 00:44:58,957
So to end this presentation,

712
00:44:58,957 --> 00:45:01,017
I'm gonna go through some lessons

713
00:45:01,017 --> 00:45:03,618
we picked up along the way.

714
00:45:03,618 --> 00:45:05,059
And before I get to that,

715
00:45:05,059 --> 00:45:09,721
couple of caveats that I think are good to mention,

716
00:45:09,721 --> 00:45:12,782
because we do things in a special way.

717
00:45:12,782 --> 00:45:16,263
First is that Clash is an eight-year-old free-to-play game.

718
00:45:17,365 --> 00:45:22,567
It's a pretty venerable age for a game, pretty venerable age for a free to play game.

719
00:45:22,567 --> 00:45:27,309
And of course, that affects how we approach things, how we see things.

720
00:45:27,309 --> 00:45:34,032
And the takeaways presented here can be a bit specific to those and operating older live games in general.

721
00:45:34,032 --> 00:45:38,834
We have fairly small teams, and this is a thing that.

722
00:45:39,990 --> 00:45:41,991
Small means different things in different companies.

723
00:45:41,991 --> 00:45:48,613
For us, small means that the Clash of Clans team is 20 developers, sorry, 20 people with

724
00:45:48,613 --> 00:45:51,734
12 developers and 8 people working in support roles.

725
00:45:51,734 --> 00:45:58,157
Of course, this means that it affects and molds our thinking on how we approach things,

726
00:45:58,157 --> 00:45:59,937
how we work around things.

727
00:46:00,237 --> 00:46:05,381
how we plan things in a big way. We don't have small teams for the sake of having small teams.

728
00:46:05,381 --> 00:46:09,525
Of course it would be nice to have big teams and produce a lot of content, but we actually believe

729
00:46:09,525 --> 00:46:16,190
as a company that small teams let us deliver the best product and it lets people have maximum

730
00:46:16,190 --> 00:46:21,755
ownership over what they do and that together just brings us to the best results. And the

731
00:46:21,755 --> 00:46:27,279
ownership thing is actually super important overall in this whole thing and that's my third point.

732
00:46:27,279 --> 00:46:29,361
The game teams at Supercell...

733
00:46:30,077 --> 00:46:37,182
have full ownership over their games. There's nothing that can't be decided in the game team,

734
00:46:37,182 --> 00:46:41,605
no one comes to second guess your decisions, it's all you all the way.

735
00:46:42,372 --> 00:46:46,115
I don't think the journey that we had in the past two years would have been possible in

736
00:46:46,115 --> 00:46:51,260
any other kind of a structure, since it's hard to imagine someone having patience towards

737
00:46:51,260 --> 00:46:56,964
a game team that says, well, we'll just work on these other things for two years and then

738
00:46:56,964 --> 00:46:58,285
we'll look at the revenue problem.

739
00:46:58,285 --> 00:47:04,330
I think we could do it because we are just responsible to ourselves and we really believed

740
00:47:04,330 --> 00:47:08,134
that this is the best thing to do, but in a different structure, it might be hard or

741
00:47:08,134 --> 00:47:08,674
even impossible.

742
00:47:09,727 --> 00:47:14,010
The first takeaway I have is, you really need to understand your game.

743
00:47:14,010 --> 00:47:17,653
Each game is a unique little snowflake.

744
00:47:17,653 --> 00:47:22,197
Each one has its own problems and its own solutions.

745
00:47:22,197 --> 00:47:29,344
And if you go full circle from the bold claim, I think Battle Pass or Gold Pass wouldn't

746
00:47:29,344 --> 00:47:31,766
have been a success two years ago.

747
00:47:31,766 --> 00:47:33,607
Because if we didn't understand...

748
00:47:34,600 --> 00:47:37,341
the fundamental problems that we had in the game,

749
00:47:37,341 --> 00:47:40,423
we would have done Gold Pass and have it land

750
00:47:40,423 --> 00:47:43,344
in a ground that just simply isn't fertile

751
00:47:43,344 --> 00:47:45,645
and or a game that's not ready for it.

752
00:47:45,645 --> 00:47:47,505
If we didn't have the magic items,

753
00:47:47,505 --> 00:47:50,267
we wouldn't have rewards for the Gold Pass.

754
00:47:50,267 --> 00:47:53,948
If we didn't have content for the maxed out players,

755
00:47:53,948 --> 00:47:57,169
Gold Pass wouldn't be interesting to them.

756
00:47:57,169 --> 00:48:01,631
If we didn't fix the, remove the barriers to upgrading

757
00:48:01,631 --> 00:48:02,871
for Town Hall 9s and 10s,

758
00:48:03,895 --> 00:48:06,837
they wouldn't care about the progression rewards in the gold pass.

759
00:48:06,837 --> 00:48:11,759
So I truly believe that the gold pass wouldn't have been a success if we had

760
00:48:11,759 --> 00:48:12,539
done it two years ago.

761
00:48:12,539 --> 00:48:18,902
Our process for understanding the game is, starts with feedback.

762
00:48:18,902 --> 00:48:23,604
And we think that you should take all the feedback you can get.

763
00:48:23,604 --> 00:48:25,045
Be a sponge for feedback.

764
00:48:25,045 --> 00:48:28,827
And the trick is that you listen to everything,

765
00:48:28,827 --> 00:48:31,848
but you don't need to believe everything or you don't need to react to

766
00:48:31,848 --> 00:48:32,228
everything.

767
00:48:33,419 --> 00:48:36,461
but listening to everything allows you to sort of form,

768
00:48:36,461 --> 00:48:40,865
formulate a picture of the world of

769
00:48:40,865 --> 00:48:44,748
how is this, how is the reality really looking?

770
00:48:44,748 --> 00:48:46,349
What does it look like?

771
00:48:46,349 --> 00:48:48,291
Where are the real problems?

772
00:48:48,291 --> 00:48:50,332
People say different things,

773
00:48:50,332 --> 00:48:52,174
but when you listen to everything,

774
00:48:52,174 --> 00:48:53,695
then a picture starts forming.

775
00:48:53,695 --> 00:48:55,236
And then once you have that picture,

776
00:48:55,236 --> 00:48:59,139
then you can choose what to believe yourself

777
00:48:59,139 --> 00:49:01,661
and which problems to start tackling.

778
00:49:02,464 --> 00:49:03,665
Figure out your foundations.

779
00:49:03,665 --> 00:49:05,867
Our foundation is pretty simple in the end.

780
00:49:05,867 --> 00:49:09,329
It wasn't a simple process to discover it,

781
00:49:09,329 --> 00:49:10,410
but in the end, it's pretty simple.

782
00:49:10,410 --> 00:49:12,411
The heart of the game,

783
00:49:12,411 --> 00:49:16,034
the ultimate foundation of the game is the village.

784
00:49:16,034 --> 00:49:20,157
Clash is really a game about building your village.

785
00:49:20,157 --> 00:49:23,019
It's, you might kind of, from the outside,

786
00:49:23,019 --> 00:49:26,101
think that it's a combat game, it's a tower defense game.

787
00:49:26,101 --> 00:49:29,443
It's about attacks, it's about looting.

788
00:49:29,443 --> 00:49:30,824
It is, but it's really,

789
00:49:31,477 --> 00:49:37,462
Deep down it's about the journey of upgrading your village, making that grow, investing in

790
00:49:37,462 --> 00:49:43,248
that over time. It's the one thing that people start with, it's the one thing that people stick

791
00:49:43,248 --> 00:49:50,795
with the game for. Sort of we had this process where we were thinking about, okay so should we

792
00:49:50,795 --> 00:49:54,859
come up with a different thing for endgame players? Should we invent a new thing?

793
00:49:56,393 --> 00:50:02,078
and try to kind of find the silver bullet that solves all our problems and adds this

794
00:50:02,078 --> 00:50:07,283
new exciting thing that endgame players will play over and over again.

795
00:50:09,313 --> 00:50:11,776
it didn't really, wasn't a good idea in the end.

796
00:50:11,776 --> 00:50:17,824
So my advice would be, don't be like us, be like you, be smarter, don't search for silver

797
00:50:17,824 --> 00:50:24,051
bullets, just double down on what makes your game special and what is valuable in your

798
00:50:24,051 --> 00:50:29,097
game and then find the right solutions to that.

799
00:50:30,033 --> 00:50:36,415
Battle Pass itself, it can be a solution for your game as well, but it might not also be.

800
00:50:36,415 --> 00:50:43,198
It really depends on what your game needs. So first figure out that, and then tailor the solutions

801
00:50:43,198 --> 00:50:50,901
to those needs. Second takeaway is be generous. Be generous with the players, give them a fun

802
00:50:50,901 --> 00:50:57,103
experience, make them have a fun time. In Clash, make them have progress, make them get to the last

803
00:50:57,103 --> 00:50:57,503
levels.

804
00:50:58,602 --> 00:50:59,883
make their life enjoyable.

805
00:50:59,883 --> 00:51:04,244
And what we found in the process of the journey

806
00:51:04,244 --> 00:51:05,304
is that when we were generous,

807
00:51:05,304 --> 00:51:09,766
we got more back from the players ourselves.

808
00:51:09,766 --> 00:51:12,567
We believe that fun time and having a good time,

809
00:51:12,567 --> 00:51:18,949
enjoyable experiences, they also make you more excited.

810
00:51:18,949 --> 00:51:21,649
They make you more willing to spend on stuff.

811
00:51:21,649 --> 00:51:24,330
I think some developers would argue that

812
00:51:24,775 --> 00:51:30,258
hey if your economy is too loose then people won't have to pay anything for anything and

813
00:51:30,258 --> 00:51:37,141
they will get everything for free and it's not great. And that's not wrong, it's true, but then

814
00:51:37,141 --> 00:51:43,164
it's also true that if your economy is too stingy you will also get people who play the game forever

815
00:51:43,164 --> 00:51:50,908
but never spend any money. That's not great either because they'll reach the end of content

816
00:51:50,908 --> 00:51:53,709
without actually spending anything. And there again...

817
00:51:55,295 --> 00:52:01,218
it makes sense from our perspective to search for the sweet spot and give people those great

818
00:52:01,218 --> 00:52:09,143
deals that let them spend a little bit and enjoy your content and then both sides win.

819
00:52:09,143 --> 00:52:15,447
Battle passes as such can be a great tool to find a sweet spot because like I said earlier

820
00:52:15,447 --> 00:52:23,371
you can make it a great deal, immense value, but it's only once per month so economy is still

821
00:52:23,371 --> 00:52:23,832
protected.

822
00:52:25,205 --> 00:52:30,146
So, my last point of the talk, last takeaway.

823
00:52:30,146 --> 00:52:33,147
It's always worth it to focus on the long term.

824
00:52:33,147 --> 00:52:38,448
And when we were working on the goal past last year,

825
00:52:38,448 --> 00:52:41,369
our goal wasn't really to make the papers.

826
00:52:41,369 --> 00:52:45,711
Our goal was to fix a problem

827
00:52:45,711 --> 00:52:49,152
and provide a fun, delightful experience to our players.

828
00:52:49,993 --> 00:52:55,074
And that sort of needs to be the way you think about things, we think.

829
00:52:55,074 --> 00:53:02,296
So you always have your eyes on the horizon, you work on problems that matter, you keep chipping

830
00:53:02,296 --> 00:53:07,217
away, making the game better, making your players happier, making sure that your team is working

831
00:53:07,217 --> 00:53:14,579
well and everyone's happy working on the game. You need to of course know your fundamentals,

832
00:53:14,579 --> 00:53:17,360
you need to have a plan, you need to challenge yourselves.

833
00:53:17,922 --> 00:53:21,905
And sometimes the features that you have planned out don't work.

834
00:53:21,905 --> 00:53:23,266
That's okay. Be patient.

835
00:53:23,266 --> 00:53:27,048
You need longevity to actually make it this long.

836
00:53:27,048 --> 00:53:32,331
And eight years might sound like a long time for a game to run.

837
00:53:32,331 --> 00:53:35,854
For us, we sort of feel that it can be just the beginning.

